05023nam a22007575i 9780226701455DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019053423  a9780226701455  a(DE-B1597)570913  a(OCoLC)1175922359  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPR571b.N47 2020 4aPN603 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809.9145223  aEC 5174qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/20599:120191 aNersessian, Anahid, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Calamity Form :bOn Poetry and Social Life /cAnahid Nersessian. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b10 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tIntroduction -- t1: Parataxis; or, Modern Gardens -- t2: Wordsworth’s Obscurity -- t3: Keats and Catachresis -- t4: Apostrophe: Clouds -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRomanticism coincided with two major historical developments: the Industrial Revolution, and with it, a turning point in our relationship to the earth, its inhabitants, and its climate. Drawing on Marxism and philosophy of science, The Calamity Form shines new light on Romantic poetry, identifying a number of rhetorical tropes used by writers to underscore their very failure to make sense of our move to industrialization. Anahid Nersessian explores works by Friedrich Hölderlin, William Wordsworth, John Keats, and others to argue that as the human and ecological costs of industry became clear, Romantic poetry adopted formal strategies—among them parataxis, the setting of elements side by side in a manner suggestive of postindustrial dissonance, and apostrophe, here an address to an absent or vanishing natural environment—as it tried and failed to narrate the calamities of capitalism. These tropes reflect how Romantic authors took their bewilderment and turned it into a poetics: a theory of writing, reading, and understanding poetry as an eminently critical act. Throughout, Nersessian pushes back against recent attempts to see literature as a source of information on par with historical or scientific data, arguing instead for an irreducibility of poetic knowledge. Revealing the ways in which these Romantic works are of their time but not about it, The Calamity Form ultimately exposes the nature of poetry’s relationship to capital—and capital’s ability to hide how it works.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnglish poetryy18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFigures of speech. 0aPoetry, Moderny18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPoetry, Moderny19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aRomanticismxHistory and criticism. 0aRomanticismzEnglandxHistory and criticismy18th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aMarxism.  aRomantic poetry.  acapitalism.  aclimate change.  afigurative language.  apoetics.  apoetry.  atropes.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226701455423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226701455/original  a978-3-11-069309-6  University